, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Haw","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haw(e)</i> which, like <i>Daw(e)</i>, was probably a rhyming pet form of Middle English <i>Raw</i> (Ralph). Similar rhyming pet forms of other Anglo-Norman male personal names beginning with <i>R-</i> are found in <i>Hick</i> and <i>Dick</i> for <i>Rick</i> (Richard) and <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i> for <i>Rob(ert)</i>. See also   Hawkin  .","English: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from Middle English <i>hawe</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>haga</i> or Old Norse <i>hagi</i>). Compare   Haugh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 何 and 賀, see   He   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Hawes was born in 1445, in Middlesex, England, his father, Sir William Hawes, was 37 and his mother, Elizabeth Joseph, was 21. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Johanna Moore. His occupation is listed as alderman in St Bartholomew by The Royal Exchange, London, England, United Kingdom. He died in 1478, in Milton Malsor, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1445–1478":"1445–1478","1444–Female":"1444–Surnud","1464–1513":"1464–1513","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1408–1469":"1408–1469","1424–1491":"1424